  </div>
</section>


<div class="occlss-wrapper">


  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Browser support</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-5">
      <p>Reflex falls back to an inline-block layout for browsers that do not support flexbox. Reflex uses some css hacks to help the inline-block layout work on older browsers. It's important to note that some of the features of flexbox do not have an equivalent
        in the inline-block fallback so not everything will work in the fallback, but <strong>your layout will remain intact.</strong></p>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-7">
      <p class="alert">If you want to use the layout with breakpoints in ie8 and below you will need to use <a href="https://github.com/scottjehl/Respond" target="_blank">respond.js</a> which enables media query support in those browsers via JavaScript and <a href="https://github.com/afarkas/html5shiv"
          target="_blank">html5Shiv</a> if you wish to use html5 elements such as <code>section</code></p>

      <p class="alert">It is possible for this framework to support ie6. You can make a tiny change to enable support but it greatly increases the filesize of the css. Look in <a href="https://github.com/leejordan/reflex/blob/master/scss/reflex/_mixins.scss#L20">_mixins.scss (Sass)</a>        or <a href="https://github.com/leejordan/reflex/blob/master/less/reflex/mixins.less#L19">mixins.less (LESS)</a> for the commented line.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Semantic markup</h2>
      <p>You don't have to use <code>div</code> for your layout and ideally you should use the most semantically appropriate markup for your use case with no visible difference.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-4">
      <h3>Divs</h3>

      <pre>&lt;div class="occlss-layout"&gt;
  &lt;div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--6"&gt;
      &lt;content&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-4">
      <h3>Unordered list</h3>

      <pre>&lt;ul class="occlss-layout"&gt;
  &lt;li class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--6"&gt;
      &lt;content&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</pre>

    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-4">
      <h3>Html5 elements</h3>

      <pre>&lt;section class="occlss-layout"&gt;
  &lt;article class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--6"&gt;
      &lt;content&gt;
  &lt;/article&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;</pre>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Numbered columns</h2>
      <p>By default reflex is a 12 column layout but this can be easily changed. Regardless of how many columns you need, you will likely require extra control over the breakpoints at which your layout columns revert to 100% width. To do this you will need
        to use these modifier classes which determine layout columns at various viewport sizes. A layout built using numbered columns in this way will remain fully intact in the inline-block fallback.</p>

      <p>The reflex layout breakpoints can be easily re-defined but are set to these values by default:</p>
      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Class prefix</th>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--</td>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--xs-</td>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-</td>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--md-</td>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--lg-</td>
              <td>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--xlg-</td>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th>Collapses at</th>
              <td>does not collapse</td>
              <td>&lt; 480px</td>
              <td>&lt; 768px</td>
              <td>&lt; 992px</td>
              <td>&lt; 1200px</td>
              <td>&lt; 1600px</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

<div class="occlss-wrapper">
  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Auto columns</h2>
      <p>You can add any number of auto sizing <code>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--auto</code> columns to a <code>layout</code> and therefore avoid using numbered columns. You can also use the regular breakpoints to determine when your columns revert
        to 100% width. A layout built using auto columns will not remain fully intact in the inline-block fallback and will not work properly in ie10 due to it's limited flexbox support but if this is a concern, you could use JavaScript for that.</p>
      <div class="occlss-layout">
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--auto example-col">
          occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--auto
        </div>
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--auto example-col">
          occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--auto
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="occlss-layout">
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-auto example-col">
          occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-auto
        </div>
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-auto example-col">
          occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-auto
        </div>
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--md-auto example-col">
          occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--md-auto
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Flexbox direction and axis</h2>
      <p>
        To understand how this layout works, you'll need to first understand how flexbox works, especially in relation to the cross axis and main axis. There's a pretty good <a href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/" target="_blank">introduction to flexbox here</a>        but here's a quick demo of the main points: flex direction, main axis, and cross axis.
      </p>
      <div class="occlss-layout" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-6 occlss-layout--direction-row occlss-layout--align-center occlss-layout--justify-space-between example-col">
          <h3>row</h3>
          <p>
            &#8596; main axis
          </p>
          <p>
            &#8597; cross axis
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-6 occlss-layout--align-center example-col">
          <h3>column</h3>
          <p>
            &#8597; main axis
          </p>
          <p>
            &#8596; cross axis
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        By default any <code>occlss-layout</code> element is set to <code>flex-direction: row</code> and the main axis therefore follows the horizontal direction.
      </p>
      <p>
        By default any <code>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--x</code> element is set to <code>flex-direction: column</code> and the main axis therefore follows the vertical direction.
      </p>
      <p>
        This will become important when you are using the modifier classes which typically act upon either the main or cross axis</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

<div class="occlss-wrapper">
  <section class="occlss-layout">
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h2>Layout modifiers</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <h3>Layout wrapping</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-8">
      <p>By default, the <code>flex-wrap</code> property of a <code>display: flex</code> element is set to <code>nowrap</code> but because this is a layout framework we generally need our layout to wrap so we explcitly set <code>flex-wrap: wrap</code> on
        our <code>layout</code> element</p>
      <p><code>occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--x</code> elements do not wrap by default, but you can make them do so by using the modifier <code>occlss-layout--wrap</code>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--sm-4">
      <p class="alert">In the inline-block fallback your layout columns will always wrap when they add up to 100% width (12 column by default).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="occlss-layout__col occlss-layout__col--12">
      <div class="occlss-layout example-section">
